In Java, a thread needs an entry point to know where to start when we
want it to run : this entry point can be any object implementing the
[Runnable](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/lang/Runnable.html)
interface. For this exercise, we give you a small implementation of the
[Runnable](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/lang/Runnable.html)
interface :
[Counter](/course/LEPL1402/ThreadsIntroduction/Counter.java), a small
class increasing an int variable `rnd` times.

You can download the [IntelliJ
Project](/course/LEPL1402/ThreadsIntroduction/LEPL1402_ThreadsIntroduction.zip)
that contains few tests to help you.

``` java
public class Counter implements Runnable {

    private int count;
    private int rnd;

    public int getCount() {
        return count;
    }

    public int getRnd(){
        return rnd;
    }

    public Counter(){
        this.count = 0;
        this.rnd = (int) ( (Math.random()*100) + 1000);
    }

    @Override
    public void run() {
        for(int i=0; i< getRnd(); i++){
            count += 1;
        }
    }

}
```

